                    <h2>Purpose</h2>
                    <p>Use Pipeline when you are conducting your Pipeline Calls in order to:</p>
        <ul>
            <li> provide visibility into the value, status, pipeline mix and additions to the pipeline</li>
            <li>help manage and predict your future revenue potential </li>
        </ul>
        <p>This will help to keep the team on track with a commonly understood set of measurements, using metrics for the pipeline questions that you care about. </p>
        <p>It will also ensure that you stay on top of the health and integrity of your pipeline to optimize your team’s future revenue. </p>
        
        
                    <div class="more_info">
                    <p>Pipeline management is one of those tasks that are too rarely treated as urgent, even though everyone accepts that the health of your pipeline is one of the most critical factors that govern the health of your business.</p>
        <p>As well as than monitoring new additions to the Pipeline - which should be monitored weekly - you should establish either a monthly or bi-weekly cadence for your strategic pipeline review sessions, depending on the sales cycle in your business. </p>
        <p>Shorter sales cycles (measured in weeks) will require more frequent pipeline review sessions. </p>
        <p> If the natural rhythm of your business maps to sales cycles that extend to three or more months, it is safe to restrict your strategic pipeline review sessions to once per month. </p>
        <p>Your Pipeline call allows you to focus on early qualification, and identify strategies and resources that you may need to maintain momentum through the pipeline.
</p>
        <p>It is likely that there is already adequate focus on the latter stages of the pipeline, because they typically contain your active and Must Win deals that are closer to closing and are the focus of this particular quarter.  </p>
        <p>However, to ensure the future health of your business, early pipeline is just as important in terms of overall pipeline health, managing your sales business, and consistently achieving quota.
</p>
        <p>Pipeline shows your team’s opportunities in Salesforce, organized by Revenue Type and Pipeline Status for a defined period. 

</p>
        <h3>Linking Pipeline to Sales Velocity</h3>
        <p>How do you know if your pipeline is actually a valid indicator of future business?  </p>
        <p>You need to identify risk in the pipeline so that you can proactively manage it.  </p>
        <p>As you consider the opportunities in the pipeline, you need to make sure that your assessment is informed by your historical performance in terms of:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>the average size of won opportunities</li>
            <li>your average winning sales cycle</li>
            <li>your win rate (measure by value, not by count)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Essentially, it comes down to being consistent and discerning about the opportunities in your pipeline, so that you can manage pipeline health and maximize win rate and opportunity value.  </p>
        <p>There are two indicators that you will have learned from past performance (in Sales Velocity) that can help you to differentiate between good and bad opportunities in your pipeline:

</p>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Average Deal Size Won</b>
            </li>
            <p>How big is a certain opportunity? Is it significantly larger than the average deal your company wins? </p>
            <p>Size has a tremendous impact on your likelihood of converting an opportunity, so it is important to compare all opportunities in your Pipeline to your Average Deal Size. 

</p>
            <li><b>Sales Cycle Duration (Won)</b>
            </li>
            <p>The age of an opportunity’s age tells you a lot about how likely you are to convert it into revenue, based on past performance. </p>
            <p>Opportunities that are in your pipeline for longer than your typical winning sales cycle are likely to be at risk. 

</p>
        </ul>
        <p>We do not recommend using ‘Weighted Pipeline’ as a measure of pipeline value.  </p>
        <p>People usually calculate Weighted Pipeline by multiplying the value of all deals in each stage of the pipeline by the probability associated with that stage, and then summing them all together.  </p>
        <p>This makes no allowance for reduction in deal size as the opportunity progresses through the funnel. </p>
        <p> It also equates $1,000,000 opportunity at 10% with a $200,000 opportunity at 50%, and that is clearly misguided. 

</p>
        <p>However, if you want to get an indication of the value that you might expect from your pipeline – remembering that it is just an indicator – you should apply Value Win Rate to the opportunities in the funnel. </p>
                    </div>
