                    <h2>How to Use with my Team</h2>
                    <p><b>Analytics</b> is the best place to start getting an overall picture of your pipeline before you dive into the details.  To do this, you must understand:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Pipeline Status</li>
            <li>Opportunity Size Analysis</li>
            <li>Adding to the Pipeline</li>
            <li>Top 5 New Opportunities This Period</li>
        </ul>
                    <div class="more_info">
                    <h3>Pipeline Status</h3>
        <p><b>Pipeline Status</b> shows your Goal, your Active pipeline, and the value of the opportunities in the pipeline that are Stalled or Inactive.  </p>
        <p>Based on the default settings, ‘Stalled’ is any opportunity that has not has a meaningful update in Salesforce in 30 days.  </p>
        <p>Similarly ‘Inactive’ is any opportunity that has not had a meaningful update in Salesforce in 60 days or more.</p>
        <p>First, you should assess whether you have enough opportunities to meet the pipeline goal. The information in the pipeline system must be pristine, continually updated to reflect progress, wins and losses. </p>
        <p>You should identify sellers who are short of goal, and understand their business development activities to add to their pipeline. </p>
        <p>Everyone must understand the language being used, and the seller must take care to accurately record the value of each opportunity. </p>
        <p>However, if you focus solely on the value of the pipeline, you will have incomplete information that may be misleading.</p>
        <p>Pipeline Status gives you the current state of your pipeline for a specific Revenue Type, separating out Active, Stalled and Inactive opportunities.  The apparent value of your pipeline can be misleading if you only look at the total value. It is always more prudent to look at the gap between Active and Goal, rather than total pipeline value. You will usually find some indicator of risk if an opportunity is either Stalled or Inactive.</p>
        <p>When an opportunity is Stalled, it usually means that the seller is either paying insufficient attention to it (or not updating Salesforce) or that access to, or contact with, the customer has reduced. In either case, there is a need to coach the opportunity or encourage more diligent performance.</p>
        <p>There is rarely a good reason for an opportunity to be Inactive. If the opportunity belongs in the pipeline, then it needs to be worked.  The only exception to this rule might be your ‘renewals-type‘ or ‘maintenance-type’ opportunities, where you record these in your CRM as open opportunities with a close date 12 months into the future, on the contract renewal date.  You should record such opportunities in Salesforce as a separate Revenue Type to separate them from your overall pipeline risk analysis.</p>
        <p>In a proportion of cases, Inactive opportunities are deals that should have been closed out because the opportunity has been lost.  In other situations, the customer’s priorities have shifted and the opportunity is deferred, or it was never a qualified opportunity in the first place. Occasionally, opportunities may be Inactive because a seller has too many opportunities to work.</p>
        <p>It is important that Inactive opportunities are appropriately managed. Closing out deals that are in fact lost, or asking Marketing to re-engage the customer in a marketing nurture campaign.</p>
        <p>To maximize the value from your pipeline, both in actual revenue terms and as a compass to guide the business, you need to look at the opportunities that can potentially undermine the value in your pipeline, or bring risk and vulnerabilities to your future business.</p>
        <h3>Opportunity Size Analysis</h3>
        <p>If you want to fill a barrel with rocks and maximize the capacity of the barrel, you have to fill the gaps between the rocks with stones or pebbles. </p>
        <p>It’s the same with your pipeline. Experienced sellers will understand that relying on a small number of big deals is risky, and they will balance their opportunity portfolio with smaller deals in order to keep the numbers moving, in case the big rock falls off the cliff. </p>
        <p>Understanding the balance of the pipeline based on size helps you to assess your risk in the pipeline.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Stones</b> would be your average opportunity size that you typically win. These are the deals that you know how to win and don't have any usual risk associated with them by virtue of their size alone.</li>
            <li><b>Rocks</b> are deals that are larger than normal and would represent significant risk if lost.  Large deals are great, but usually require extra focus if you want to maximize the chance of winning.  They can have a material impact on the size of your pipeline, and you need to qualify rigorously to ensure that you don't have a false sense of security about your pipeline strength.</li>
            <li><b>Pebbles</b> are opportunities that are smaller than average and may put an unreasonable demand on resources. Smaller-than-average deals often require the same level of effort as a Stone, but the return for effort is obviously smaller. Sellers that have a high balance of pebbles in their pipeline may need help to create value with the customer to increase the deal size.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The size of the opportunity has a tremendous impact on your likelihood of converting an opportunity, so it is important to compare all opportunities in your Pipeline to your Average Deal Size Won.</p>
        <p>Additionally, you should review the Average Sales Cycle Duration (won) in Sales Velocity, and compare the age of your existing opportunities to this duration.</p>
        <h3>Adding to the Pipeline</h3>
        <p><b>Adding to the Pipeline</b> shows the quantity of opportunities that are added to the pipeline in the period being reviewed, and the number that was Closed Won or Closed Lost.  </p>
        <p>Because the number of open opportunities in the pipeline is reduced by any closed opportunity, you can subtract the total of closed opportunities from the number of opportunities added, to identify the 'delta' - the change to the number of opportunities in your pipeline. </p>
        <p>Looking at the details behind this graph is a very quick way to see which sellers are adding opportunities, and you might spend a minute recognizing your leading pipeline builders.</p>
        <p>This is your Pipeline flow. Every month, your Pipeline loses a certain percentage of its open opportunities as either Closed-Won or Closed-Lost. To prevent your Pipeline from shrinking, you need to create more new open opportunities than you lost or Closed Won, which means carefully tracking your Pipeline’s flow over time and increasing your Pipeline commensurately.</p>
        <p>Getting new opportunities into the top of your sales funnel is the source of your raw material. Without that raw material, you can’t build a sales business.  It’s not enough to simply add new opportunities to your Pipeline – you must add enough to replace the opportunities that have flowed out as Won and Lost Deals.  The important points here are that you need to maintain continuous focus on filling the funnel, and that each seller has to own this problem for themselves.</p>
        <h3>Top 5 New Opportunities This Period</h3>
        <p><b>Top 5 New Opportunities This Period</b> shows the biggest five new opportunities that have been added in the period.  It is a quick way for you to keep focus on early qualification or early development of these opportunities.  </p>
        <p>Early stage opportunity development is a key trait of winning deals, and you can quickly mark these opportunities as Must Win or Must Develop as appropriate.</p>
        <p>Consider the following questions to guide your selection of Must Win deals:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Is the opportunity of sufficient value that merits specific focused resources?</li>
            <li>Is it a strategic competitive replacement to establish a beachhead for future business?</li>
            <li>Is this a strategic or marquee account?</li>
            <li>Does it provide an opportunity to establish a reference account for a new product?</li>
            <li>Are you are defending a position against an important competitor?</li>
            <li>Does it provide an opportunity to establish a reference customer in a new industry?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Must Develop opportunities, like Must Win opportunities, are strategically important to win, but are not the deals you are planning to close in the immediate term. </p>
        <p>The key thing is that you proactively decide to adopt a Develop Strategy that positions you for a future sale.</p>
                    </div>
