                <div class="point_text">
                    <h2>Top Risks to Pipeline</h2>
                    <p>This section deals with the major risks to your pipeline:</p>
                    <ul>
                    <li>Not Enough Being Added to The Pipeline</li>
                    <li>Stalled and Inactive Opportunities</li>
                    <li>Opportunities Outside Your Sweet Spot Size</li>
                    <li>Slow Moving Opportunities</li>
                    <li>History of Low Value Win Rate (versus Number Win Rate)</li>
                    </ul>
                    
       
                   <div class="more_info">
                    
        
            <h3>Not Enough Being Added to The Pipeline</h3>
            <p>This is pretty obvious, but the biggest risk to pipeline is not maintaining a rigorous focus on adding opportunities in the top of the funnel.</p>
            <p>Getting new opportunities into the top of your sales funnel is the source of your raw material. Without that raw material, you can’t build a sales business.</p>
            <p> It’s not enough to simply add new opportunities to your Pipeline – you must add enough to replace the opportunities that have flowed out as Won and Lost Deals.</p>
            <h3>Stalled and Inactive Opportunities</h3>
            <p>The value of your pipeline is overstated if you have Stalled or Inactive opportunities. </p>
            <p>It is likely that Stalled opportunities indicate that some there is new risk in a deal, whereas Inactive opportunities probably don't belong in the pipeline at all.</p>
            <p>Without considering the actual status of Stalled and Inactive opportunities, you cannot get a true value of the pipeline, and that means that your future business is at risk.</p>
            <h3>Opportunities Outside Your Sweet Spot Size</h3>
            <p>We have all fallen at this hurdle – pursuing those enormous opportunities that can make the year or quarter without having muscle memory on how to do a deal of this scale. </p>
            <p> If your pipeline has a disproportionate number of very large deals that are substantially larger than the size of deals that you normally win, it's likely that there is considerable risk to your pipeline. </p>
            <p> Similarly, if your pipeline is full of many small deals, it's likely that you will spend equal resources on each of these deals, meaning that you will just not have enough time to win enough opportunities to make your number. </p>
            <h3>Slow Moving Opportunities</h3>
            <p>Deals that have been in your pipeline for materially longer than the time it usually takes to win a sale are unlikely to close. </p>
            <p>Be ruthless in assessing opportunities that are moving unusually slowly. It usually speaks to a lack of a Compelling Event, or suggests that an opportunity does not in fact exist.  </p>
            <p>This is why there are so many opportunities recorded as Closed Lost – No Decision.</p>
            <h3>History of Low Value Win Rate (versus Number Win Rate) </h3>
            <p>Consider your Value Win Rate compared to your Number Win Rate to assess how you might reasonably expect to perform against the total value in the pipeline. </p>
            <p>If the average size of deals won is smaller than the average of all closed deals, you should consider the impact on the expected value from your existing pipeline if this performance continues, by applying the Value Win Rate percentage to the active pipeline value.
</p>
                    </div>
                    <p><a href="javascript:void[0]" class="more_info_link">More...</a></p>
                </div>
            </li>
            <li class="clearfix">
                <div class="point_image"><img src="{!URLFOR($Resource.eLearning, 'images/icon5.png')}" /></div>
                <div class="point_text">
                    <h2>Best Practice</h2>
                    <p>Emotionally, filling the pipeline is the definitely one of the hardest part of sales. Sellers need to see the value in maintaining a full and vibrant pipeline so that they are not dependent on having to force a few deals across the line to make the number. </p>
        <p>There may be an expectation that filling the funnel is someone else’s job, but sellers need to take ownership of their own pipeline, and either build opportunities themselves or work with internal resources to make sure they are getting what they need.</p>
        
                    <div class="more_info">
                    <ul>
                    <li>Consider Sales Cycle, Average Deal Size and Value Win Rate when setting pipeline Goals.  The traditional method of applying 3x or 5x times your annual goal does consider these factors, and can be misleading.</li>
            
                      <li>Conduct Pipeline Review calls bi-weekly with each team member during the first two months of a quarter.  Begin with the Pipeline Status to review Active, Stalled and Inactive opportunities, and determine gap to Pipeline Goal.</li>
            <li>Prepare in advance. Both manager and seller should get into a habit of coming to the call with the requisite information already in hand to have a productive meeting.  Review the Pipeline status/details in Dealmaker prior to the Pipeline Review call, and prepare questions.  In the manager’s case, the questions can be for clarification, but should be mainly focused on determining what assistance or guidance can be provided. 

</li>
            <li>Review any Stalled or Inactive opportunities to determine what actions need to be taken to accelerate deals, or whether opportunities need to be purged from the sales funnel.

</li>
            <li>Separate the review of existing pipeline opportunities from a discussion about the current activity on filling the funnel.  For funnel-building activities, look at net adds both in-period and since the last call. This ensures that sellers are building pipelines that not only serve the current reporting period, but also will give positive results in the future. 

</li>
            <li>Ensure that you have a customer-evidence-based sales process in place that governs how opportunities move from one stage of the funnel to the next, getting a common sales language in the team and a better understanding of funnel velocity.  Funnel velocity is at least as important as pipeline size. A formalized sales process using customer-verifiable outcomes helps to measure your progress through the buying cycle and optimize funnel velocity.
</li>
            <li>Look for risk.  Assess Opportunity Analysis Risk to uncover any dependencies on large deals.  Review opportunity age to highlight opportunities that are lingering the funnel.</li>
        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
